{{other people||Andrei Markov (disambiguation){{!}}Andrei Markov}}

'''Andrey Andreyevich Markov Jr.''' ({{lang-ru|Андре́й Андре́евич Ма́рков}}; [[Saint Petersburg|St. Petersburg]], September 22, 1903 &ndash; [[Moscow]], October 11, 1979) was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[mathematician]], the son of the Russian mathematician [[Andrey Markov|Andrey Andreyevich Markov Sr]], and one of the key founders of the Russian school of [[constructive mathematics]] and logic. He made outstanding contributions to various areas of mathematics, including [[differential equation]]s, [[topology]], [[mathematical logic]] and the [[foundations of mathematics]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kushner|first=Boris A|title=The constructive mathematics of A. A. Markov|journal=Amer. Math. Monthly|volume=113|year=2006|issue=6|pages=559&ndash;566|mr=2231143|jstor=27641983|doi=10.2307/27641983}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|mr=2069985|last1=Glukhov|first1=M. M.|last2=Nagornyĭ|first2=N. M.|title=Andreĭ Andreevich Markov (on the centenary of his birth)|journal=Diskrete Math. Appl.|volume=14|year=2004|issue=1|pages=1&ndash;6|doi=10.1515/156939204774148776}}</ref>

His name is in particular associated with [[Markov's principle]], [[Markov's principle#Markov's rule|Markov's rule]], and [[Markov algorithm]]. An important result which he proved in 1947 was that the [[word problem for semigroups]] was unsolvable;{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} [[Emil Post]] obtained the same result independently at about the same time. In 1953 he became a member of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]].

In 1960, Markov obtained fundamental results showing that the classification of four-dimensional [[manifolds]] is [[Undecidable problem|undecidable]]: no general algorithm exists for distinguishing two arbitrary manifolds with four or more dimensions.  This is because four dimensional manifolds have sufficient flexibility to allow us to embed any algorithm{{Clarify|reason=How do you embed an algorithm in a manifold?|date=October 2018}} within their structure, so that classification of all four-manifolds would imply a solution to Turing's [[halting problem]].  This result has profound implications for the limitations of mathematical analysis.

