{{other people|Joseph Turner}}
[[File:Joseph Turner by George Dawe.jpg|thumb|Joseph Turner by [[George Dawe]]]]
'''Joseph Turner''' (1746 or 1747 &ndash; 3 August 1828) was a British academic and clergyman.

He entered [[Pembroke College, Cambridge|Pembroke College]], [[Cambridge University]] in 1763 at age 17 and was [[senior wrangler]] in 1767.  He received an [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|M.A.]] in 1770.

He was Master of Pembroke College from 1784 to 1828, and [[Dean of Norwich]] from 1790 to 1828.

He was a [[List of Vice-Chancellors of the University of Cambridge|Vice-Chancellor of Cambridge University]] in 1785&ndash;6 and 1805&ndash;6.

His only son was William Hamilton Turner, who became vicar of [[Banwell, Somerset]].<ref>{{acad|id=TNR819WH|name=Turner, William Hamilton}}</ref>

