{{Multiple issues|{{technical|date=June 2017}}{{essay-like|date=June 2017}}}}

An '''X-Value Adjustment''' ('''XVA''', '''xVA''') is a generic term referring collectively to a number of different “Valuation Adjustments” in relation to [[derivative (finance)|derivative instruments]] held by banks.<ref>[https://wiki.treasurers.org/wiki/X-Value_Adjustment X-Value Adjustment] [[Association of Corporate Treasurers]]</ref><ref>[https://www.pwc.com.au/pdf/xva-explained.pdf XVA explained]. [[PWC]], December 2015</ref> The purpose of these is twofold: primarily to hedge for possible losses due to counterparty default; but also, to determine (and hedge) the amount of capital required under [[Basel III]].  For a discussion as to the impact of xVA on the bank's overall [[balance sheet]], [[return on equity]], and [[dividend policy]], see: <ref name="Albanese et al">Claudio Albanese, Simone Caenazzo and Stephane Crepey (2016). [https://arxiv.org/pdf/1603.03012.pdf Capital Valuation Adjustment and Funding Valuation Adjustment]. ''[[Risk (magazine)|Risk Magazine]]'', May 2016.</ref>  XVA has, in many institutions, led to the creation of [[Trading desk|specialized desks]].<ref>[http://news.efinancialcareers.com/uk-en/175881/cva-traders-left-stranded-xva-becomes-big-new-acroynm CVA traders left stranded as XVA becomes big new acroynm], efinancialcareers.com. Sarah Butcher, 2014.</ref> Note that the various XVA require careful and correct aggregation without double counting.<ref name="Morini"/>

==Context==
Historically,<ref name="Youmbi"/><ref name="Morini">[http://www.aims.ac.za/assets/files/Workshops/XVA.pdf XVAs: Funding, Credit, Debit & Capital in pricing]. Massimo Morini, Banca IMI </ref><ref name="Brigo">[https://cdn.uclouvain.be/public/Exports%20reddot/csam/documents/Damiano_Brigo_Nonlinear_Valuation_and_XVA_under_Credit_Risk_Collateral_Margins_and_Funding_Costs.pdf Nonlinear valuation and XVA under credit risk, collateral margins and Funding Costs]. Prof. Damiano Brigo, Univ. Catholique de Louvain</ref><ref name="Albanese et al"/> ([[over the counter|OTC]]) [[mathematical finance#Derivatives pricing|derivative pricing]] has relied on the [[Black-Scholes]]' [[risk-neutral measure|risk neutral pricing framework]], under the assumptions of funding at the risk free rate and the ability to perfectly replicate derivatives so as to fully hedge; see {{sectionlink|Black–Scholes equation|Derivation}}; {{sectionlink|Rational pricing|The replicating portfolio}}.  
This, in turn, is built on the assumption of a credit-risk-free environment.  Post [[financial crisis of 2008]], therefore, [[counterparty credit risk]] must also be considered in the valuation,<ref>[http://pure.au.dk/portal-asb-student/files/96440392/Master_Thesis_Pure.pdf  Post-Crisis Pricing of Swaps using xVAs], Christian Kjølhede & Anders Bech, Master thesis, [[Aarhus University]]</ref>  and the risk neutral value is then adjusted correspondingly. See {{sectionlink|Financial economics|Derivative pricing}} for further discussion.

==Valuation adjustments==
These calculations in overview: When the deal is [[collateral (finance)|collateralized]] then the "fair-value" is computed as before, but using the [[overnight index swap]] (OIS) curve for discounting. (The OIS is chosen here as it reflects the rate for overnight unsecured lending between banks, and is thus considered a good indicator of the interbank credit markets.)  When the deal is not collateralized then a [[credit valuation adjustment]], or '''CVA''', is added to this value; <ref name="Youmbi">[http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2511585  Derivatives Pricing after the 2007-2008 Crisis: How the Crisis Changed the Pricing Approach], Didier Kouokap Youmbi, [[Bank of England]] – [[Prudential Regulation Authority (United Kingdom)|Prudential Regulation Authority]]</ref>  essentially, the discounted [[risk-neutral|risk-neutral expectation]] of any loss due to the counterparty not performing - typically calculated under [[Monte Carlo methods in finance|a simulation framework]].<ref name="Hull_White">[http://www.fincad.com/blog/valuation-adjustments-1 VALUATION ADJUSTMENTS 1]. [[John C. Hull|John Hull]] and [[Alan White (economist)|Alan White]]</ref>  

Note that when transactions are governed by a [[ISDA Master Agreement|master agreement]] that includes [[netting]], then the expected loss from a default depends on the whole portfolio, and cannot be calculated on a transaction-by-transaction basis. The CVA (xVA) applied to a new transaction should be the incremental effect of the new transaction on portfolio CVA.<ref name="Hull_White"/>

While the CVA reflects the market value of [[counterparty credit risk]], additional ''Valuation Adjustments'' for Debit, Funding, [[regulatory capital]] and [[Margin (finance)|margin]] may similarly be added.<ref name="Green">[http://www.prmia.org/sites/default/files/PRMIA%20XVA%20Collateral%20Event.pdf XVA and Collateral: pricing and managing new liquidity risks]. Andrew Green</ref><ref name = "crepey">[https://math.maths.univ-evry.fr/crepey/papers/opinions%20REVISED.pdf XVA: About CVA, DVA, FVA and Other Market Adjustments], Discussion paper: Louis Bachelier Finance and Sustainable Growth Labex. Stephane Crepey </ref> As for CVA, these results are modeled via simulation as a function of the risk-neutral expectation  of (a) values of the underlying instrument, and the relevant market values, and (b) creditworthyness of the counterparty. As above, the various XVA require careful and correct aggregation without double counting.

These adjustments:<ref>[http://www.numerix.com/xvas-defined-profitability-puzzle XVAs Defined: The Profitability Puzzle], [[numerix]]</ref>
*'''DVA''', Debit Valuation Adjustment: analogous to CVA, an adjustment (reduction) to a derivative price due to the institution's own default risk.
*'''FVA''', Funding Valuation Adjustment, due to the funding implications of a trade that is not under a perfect [[Credit Support Annex]] (CSA); essentially the difference between the rate paid for the collateral to the bank's treasury, and the rate paid by the [[central counterparty clearing|clearinghouse]].
*'''KVA''', the Valuation Adjustment for [[capital requirement#Regulatory capital|regulatory capital]] through the life of the contract.
*'''MVA''', Margin Valuation Adjustment, refers to the costs specific to [[central counterparty clearing|centrally cleared transactions]], such as adjustments for [[initial margin]] and [[margin (finance)#Types of margin requirements|variation margin]]. It may also be calculated on the Initial Margin costs of under the global Non-centrally cleared derivatives rules.<ref name="NCCD">[https://www.bis.org/bcbs/publ/d317.htm Margin requirements for non-centrally cleared derivatives]. BCBS and IOSCO</ref>

Other adjustments are also sometimes made including TVA, for tax and RVA, for replacement of the derivative [[credit rating agency#Role in capital markets|on downgrade]]. <ref name="Green"/> FVA may be decomposed into FCA for receivables and  FBA for payables - where FCA is due to self funded borrowing spread over Libor, and  FBA due to self funded lending.  Relatedly, LVA represents the specific liquidity adjustment, while CollVA is the value of the optionality embedded in a CSA to post collateral in different currencies.  CRA , the collateral rate adjustment,  reflects the present value of the expected excess of net interest paid on cash collateral over the net interest that would be paid if the interest rate
equaled the risk-free rate.

